## Memory Leak Analysis: `ScrollTracker`

There are **three distinct problems** in this component, and they compound each other catastrophically.

---

## Problem 1: Missing Dependency Array — The Re-Registration Loop

```jsx
// ❌ No dependency array — runs after EVERY render
useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });
    window.addEventListener('resize', () => { ... });
});
//  ↑ No second argument at all
```

Without a dependency array (`[]`), `useEffect` behaves like `componentDidUpdate` — it fires after **every single render**. Here's why this creates an explosion:

```
Mount         → effect runs → adds scroll listener #1, resize listener #1
Scroll event  → setScrollY() called → re-render
Re-render     → effect runs → adds scroll listener #2, resize listener #2
Scroll event  → now TWO handlers fire → setScrollY() called TWICE → 2 re-renders
2 re-renders  → effect runs TWICE → adds scroll listeners #3 and #4...
```

The listener count grows super-linearly. Within seconds of interacting with the page, you can have hundreds of active event listeners all firing simultaneously on every scroll tick, each one triggering state updates, each state update triggering more renders, each render adding more listeners.

---

## Problem 2: Missing Cleanup — Listeners Survive Component Unmount

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });
    window.addEventListener('resize', () => { ... });
    // ❌ No return () => { removeEventListener(...) }
});
```

`window` is a global object that outlives any React component. When the user navigates away and `ScrollTracker` unmounts, React calls the cleanup function returned by `useEffect` — but **there is no cleanup function**. Every listener ever registered continues to live on `window`.

Each dead listener closes over the component's state setter functions (`setScrollY`, `setScrollDirection`, `setLastScrollY`). Even though the component is gone, those state setters hold a reference to the component's fiber node in React's internal tree, which holds references to the component's state, props, and the entire render subtree — **none of it can be garbage collected**.

The lifecycle of a single navigation cycle:

```
1st visit:  mount → register N listeners (N grows due to Problem 1)
Navigate away: unmount → cleanup? ❌ NO → N listeners persist on window
2nd visit:  mount → register N more listeners on top of existing N → 2N listeners
Navigate away: unmount → cleanup? ❌ NO → 2N listeners persist
3rd visit:  3N listeners...
```

Each visit permanently worsens the situation.

---

## Problem 3: Anonymous Functions Are Unremovable

```jsx
// ❌ A new, unique function object is created on every call
window.addEventListener('scroll', () => {
    setScrollY(window.scrollY);
});

// Even if you tried to clean up like this — it WON'T work:
window.removeEventListener('scroll', () => {
    setScrollY(window.scrollY); // ← Different function object reference!
});
```

`removeEventListener` requires **the exact same function reference** that was passed to `addEventListener`. Arrow functions defined inline are new objects every time — JavaScript has no way to compare them by body. Without a named reference stored in a variable, the listener is **permanently irremovable**. This makes cleanup structurally impossible even if you tried to add a `return` statement.

---

## Bonus Problem: Stale Closure on `lastScrollY`

```jsx
// lastScrollY is captured from the closure when the effect runs
// On the first render, lastScrollY is 0 and stays 0 forever in this handler
useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', () => {
        setScrollDirection(currentScrollY > lastScrollY ? 'down' : 'up');
        //                                   ↑ Always 0! Stale closure.
    });
}, []); // Even if [] were added, lastScrollY would be stale
```

With a proper `[]` dependency array (running the effect only once), the scroll handler captures `lastScrollY` from the initial render where it's `0`. The direction logic would always compare against `0`, not the actual previous scroll position. The fix is `useRef` — a ref's `.current` value is always live and current inside any closure.

---

## React 18 Strict Mode Makes This Worse in Development

React 18 Strict Mode intentionally **double-invokes effects in development** by running: `mount → effect → cleanup → remount → effect`. This is designed specifically to surface missing cleanup bugs. With this component:

```
Strict Mode mounts component
→ Effect runs → adds scroll + resize listeners
→ Cleanup runs → ❌ No cleanup fn → listeners remain attached
→ Re-mounts component  
→ Effect runs AGAIN → adds duplicate listeners
→ Now 4 listeners after a single mount
→ Each scroll event fires all 4 handlers → 4 state updates → 4 renders → 8 new listeners...
```

The bug that might take 10 navigation cycles to notice in production becomes a browser freeze in 3 seconds of development testing. This is by design — Strict Mode is telling you your cleanup is broken.

---

## The Corrected Component

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect, useRef } from 'react';

function ScrollTracker() {
    const [scrollY, setScrollY] = useState(0);
    const [scrollDirection, setScrollDirection] = useState('none');
    // useRef instead of useState: mutations don't trigger re-renders,
    // and the value is always current inside any closure — no stale capture.
    const lastScrollYRef = useRef(0);

    useEffect(() => {
        // Named function references — REQUIRED for removeEventListener to work.
        // Arrow functions create a new object on every call; removeEventListener
        // uses reference equality, so anonymous functions can never be removed.
        function handleScroll() {
            const currentScrollY = window.scrollY;

            // lastScrollYRef.current is always the live value, never stale,
            // even though this function was defined once at mount time.
            setScrollDirection(currentScrollY > lastScrollYRef.current ? 'down' : 'up');
            lastScrollYRef.current = currentScrollY; // Update ref synchronously
            setScrollY(currentScrollY);
        }

        function handleResize() {
            console.log('Window resized, recalculating...');
            setScrollY(window.scrollY);
        }

        window.addEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
        window.addEventListener('resize', handleResize);

        // Cleanup function: React calls this when the component unmounts
        // AND before re-running the effect (though with [], it only runs once).
        // The named references here match exactly what was passed above —
        // removeEventListener will find and remove the correct listeners.
        return () => {
            window.removeEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
            window.removeEventListener('resize', handleResize);
        };

    }, []); // Empty array: run once on mount, clean up once on unmount.
            // No dependencies because handleScroll/handleResize only use
            // refs and stable setter functions (setScrollY, setScrollDirection),
            // none of which change between renders.

    return (
        <div style={{ position: 'fixed', top: 10, right: 10, padding: '10px', background: '#333', color: '#fff' }}>
            <p>Scroll Y: {scrollY}</p>
            <p>Direction: {scrollDirection}</p>
        </div>
    );
}

export default ScrollTracker;
```

---

## Summary of All Fixes

| Problem | Root Cause | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| Listeners added on every render | No `[]` dependency array | Add `[]` — effect runs only on mount |
| Listeners survive unmount | No cleanup function | Return cleanup fn that calls `removeEventListener` |
| Cleanup can't target the right function | Anonymous inline arrow functions | Use named function declarations with stable references |
| Stale `lastScrollY` in handler | Closed over state value frozen at mount | Replace `useState` with `useRef` for the comparison value |

The mental model to internalize: **every `addEventListener` must have a matching `removeEventListener` with the same reference, wired into `useEffect`'s cleanup return**. Anything registered on a global object (`window`, `document`, `navigator`, `WebSocket`, `setInterval`) will outlive your component unless you explicitly remove it.

